NAME
	call_out - start a callout

SYNOPSIS
	int call_out(string function, mixed delay, mixed args...)


DESCRIPTION
	Start a callout: schedule the given function in the current
	object to be called delay seconds from now, and return a handle
	that identifies the pending callout.  delay is an int or a float;
	a float schedules a sub-second callout.  Any further arguments
	are stored and passed to the function when the callout fires.

	The kernel layer routes the callout through its resource-limited
	execution gate, so that when the function runs it is accounted
	against the resource limits of the object's owner, the same gate
	call_limited() uses.  Callouts started from a kernel object (one
	whose name begins with /kernel/) are scheduled directly, without
	the gate.

ERRORS
	Starting a callout for a function defined in the kernel's auto
	object (other than create()), or in a light-weight object (one
	with a name of the form "object_name#-1"), results in an error.

SEE ALSO
	efun/call_out_other, efun/call_limited, kfun/call_out
